    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix memory corruption in UL reference signal generation\n\n### Summary\nThe `generate_ul_ref_sigs` function in the LTE uplink reference signal module contains multiple memory management issues that can lead to segmentation faults and undefined behavior. These issues manifest when the function is called during PHY initialization, particularly in scenarios involving different resource block allocations.\n\nThe primary problems identified are:\n1. Incorrect indexing in the debug print statement causing out-of-bounds memory access\n2. Inconsistent memory allocation/free sizes leading to potential heap corruption\n3. Incomplete initialization of reference signal arrays for certain RB configurations\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Configure eNB with mixed RB allocations including RB1 and RB2 configurations\n2. Start the eNB initialization process\n3. Observe segmentation fault during `generate_ul_ref_sigs()` execution\n4. Alternatively, run with memory debugging tools to detect heap corruption\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/LTE_REFSIG/lte_ul_ref.c`: Fixed indexing bug in debug print statement (n<<2 \u2192 n<<1)\n- `openair1/PHY/LTE_REFSIG/lte_ul_ref.c`: Corrected memory allocation/free size inconsistency for ul_ref_sigs_rx arrays\n- `openair1/PHY/LTE_REFSIG/lte_ul_ref.c`: Added complete initialization for v=1 cases in RB1/RB2 configurations\n"
}